4.1 Method Overloading (Area & Volume Calculator)
1. Aim
To write a Java program that calculates area of 2D shapes and volume of 3D shapes using method overloading.
 
2. Theory
Method overloading is a feature in Java that allows multiple methods to have the same name but different parameters (type, number, or order). It increases code readability and flexibility by allowing a single method name to perform different tasks.
In this program, method overloading is used to calculate areas and volumes of different shapes. For example, the same method name calculate() can be used for circle, rectangle, square, triangle, sphere, cylinder, cuboid, and cube, but with different parameters.
For 2D shapes:
• Circle: πr²
• Rectangle: length × breadth
• Square: side²
• Triangle: ½ × base × height
For 3D shapes:
• Sphere: (4/3)πr³
• Cylinder: πr²h
• Cuboid: l × b × h
• Cube: side³
The compiler differentiates methods based on their parameter list. This demonstrates polymorphism, which is an important concept in object-oriented programming.
 
3. Code
class Shape {

   double calculate(double r) { // Circle
       return 3.14 * r * r;
   }

   double calculate(double l, double b) { // Rectangle
       return l * b;
   }

   double calculate(int side) { // Square
       return side * side;
   }

   double calculate(double base, double height, String type) { // Triangle
       return 0.5 * base * height;
   }

   double calculateVolume(double r, String shape) { // Sphere
       return (4.0/3) * 3.14 * r * r * r;
   }

   double calculateVolume(double r, double h) { // Cylinder
       return 3.14 * r * r * h;
   }

   double calculateVolume(double l, double b, double h) { // Cuboid
       return l * b * h;
   }

   double calculateVolume(int side) { // Cube
       return side * side * side;
   }
}

public class OverloadingDemo {
   public static void main(String[] args) {
       Shape s = new Shape();

       System.out.println("Circle Area: " + s.calculate(5));
       System.out.println("Rectangle Area: " + s.calculate(4, 6));
       System.out.println("Square Area: " + s.calculate(4));
       System.out.println("Triangle Area: " + s.calculate(5, 6, "triangle"));

       System.out.println("Sphere Volume: " + s.calculateVolume(3, "sphere"));
       System.out.println("Cylinder Volume: " + s.calculateVolume(3, 5));
       System.out.println("Cuboid Volume: " + s.calculateVolume(2, 3, 4));
       System.out.println("Cube Volume: " + s.calculateVolume(3));
   }
}
 
