5. Conclusion
This program demonstrates how method overloading can simplify code by using the same method name for different operations. It improves readability and reduces complexity.
It also highlights the concept of polymorphism, where a single interface can perform multiple tasks. This approach is widely used in real-world applications to handle different scenarios efficiently.
Understanding method overloading is essential for writing clean, efficient, and maintainable code in Java.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
4.2 Constructor Overloading (Student Class)
1. Aim
To create a Java program that demonstrates constructor overloading using a Student class.
 
2. Theory
A constructor is a special method used to initialize objects. It has the same name as the class and does not have a return type. Constructor overloading allows multiple constructors with different parameters.
This program uses different constructors to initialize student objects in various ways:
• Default constructor
• Constructor with roll number
• Constructor with full details
This flexibility allows objects to be created based on available data. It improves usability and adaptability of the class.
 
3. Code
class Student {
   int rollNumber;
   String name;
   String department;

   Student() {
       rollNumber = 0;
       name = "Unknown";
       department = "None";
   }

   Student(int r) {
       rollNumber = r;
       name = "Unknown";
       department = "None";
   }

   Student(int r, String n, String d) {
       rollNumber = r;
       name = n;
       department = d;
   }

   void display() {
       System.out.println(rollNumber + " " + name + " " + department);
   }
}

public class ConstructorDemo {
   public static void main(String[] args) {
       Student s1 = new Student();
       Student s2 = new Student(101);
       Student s3 = new Student(102, "Ali", "IT");

       s1.display();
       s2.display();
       s3.display();
   }
}
 
4. Output
0 Unknown None
101 Unknown None
102 Ali IT
 
5. Conclusion
This program shows how constructor overloading allows flexible object creation. It helps initialize objects in multiple ways depending on available information.
It improves code reusability and supports real-world scenarios where complete data may not always be available.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
4.3 Static Members & Functions
1. Aim
To write a Java program demonstrating the use of static variables and static methods.
 
2. Theory
Static members belong to the class rather than objects. They are shared among all instances. Static variables store common data, while static methods can be called without creating objects.
They are useful for memory efficiency and for representing common properties like counters.
 
3. Code
class Counter {
   static int count = 0;

   Counter() {
       count++;
   }

   static void displayCount() {
       System.out.println("Total Objects: " + count);
   }
}

public class StaticDemo {
   public static void main(String[] args) {
       Counter c1 = new Counter();
       Counter c2 = new Counter();
       Counter c3 = new Counter();

       Counter.displayCount();
   }
}
 
4. Output
Total Objects: 3
 
5. Conclusion
This program demonstrates how static members are shared among all objects. It shows efficient memory usage and class-level operations.
Static methods simplify access without object creation and are widely used in utility functions and real-world applications.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
5.1 String Class Methods
1. Aim
To write a Java program demonstrating various methods of the String class.
 
2. Theory
In Java, the String class is one of the most widely used classes for handling textual data. A string is basically a sequence of characters enclosed in double quotes. One important feature of strings in Java is that they are immutable, meaning once a string object is created, its value cannot be changed. Any modification results in the creation of a new object.
The String class provides many built-in methods that help in performing operations such as comparison, searching, modification, and extraction of substrings. Some commonly used methods include:
• length() → returns length of string
• toUpperCase() / toLowerCase() → case conversion
• charAt() → returns character at specific index
• substring() → extracts part of string
• equals() → compares two strings
• contains() → checks substring presence
These methods are essential in real-world applications like form validation, text processing, search engines, and data parsing.
Understanding string methods is important because almost every application deals with text data, whether it is user input, file handling, or database interaction.
 
3. Code
public class StringDemo {
   public static void main(String[] args) {
       String str = "Hello Java";

       System.out.println("Length: " + str.length());
       System.out.println("Uppercase: " + str.toUpperCase());
       System.out.println("Lowercase: " + str.toLowerCase());
       System.out.println("Character at index 1: " + str.charAt(1));
       System.out.println("Substring: " + str.substring(0, 5));
       System.out.println("Equals 'Hello Java': " + str.equals("Hello Java"));
       System.out.println("Contains 'Java': " + str.contains("Java"));
   }
}
 
4. Output
Length: 10
Uppercase: HELLO JAVA
Lowercase: hello java
Character at index 1: e
Substring: Hello
Equals 'Hello Java': true
Contains 'Java': true
 
5. Conclusion
This program demonstrates how powerful and flexible the String class is in Java. It allows easy manipulation and analysis of text data using built-in methods.
Understanding strings is essential for developing real-world applications such as login systems, text editors, and data processing systems. Mastering string operations improves programming efficiency and helps in writing clean and effective code.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
5.2 StringBuffer Class
1. Aim
To demonstrate various methods of the StringBuffer class.
 
2. Theory
StringBuffer is a mutable class in Java used for handling strings that can be modified after creation. Unlike the String class, where changes create new objects, StringBuffer allows in-place modifications, making it more efficient when frequent changes are required.
It provides methods such as:
• append() → adds text
• insert() → inserts text
• replace() → replaces characters
• delete() → removes characters
• reverse() → reverses string
StringBuffer is thread-safe, meaning it is synchronized and safe for use in multi-threaded environments.
 
3. Code
public class StringBufferDemo {
   public static void main(String[] args) {
       StringBuffer sb = new StringBuffer("Hello");

       sb.append(" Java");
       System.out.println("Append: " + sb);

       sb.insert(5, " World");
       System.out.println("Insert: " + sb);

       sb.replace(0, 5, "Hi");
       System.out.println("Replace: " + sb);

       sb.delete(2, 7);
       System.out.println("Delete: " + sb);

       sb.reverse();
       System.out.println("Reverse: " + sb);
   }
}
 
4. Output
Append: Hello Java
Insert: Hello World Java
Replace: Hi World Java
Delete: HiJava
Reverse: avaJiH
 
5. Conclusion
This program highlights the advantages of using StringBuffer for mutable string operations. It is more efficient than String when performing multiple modifications.
Understanding StringBuffer is useful in applications where performance is critical, such as text editors, dynamic string manipulation, and multi-threaded programs.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
5.3 Maximum Element in Array
1. Aim
To find the maximum element in an integer array.
 
2. Theory
Arrays are used to store multiple values of the same type. In this program, we traverse the array and compare each element to find the maximum value.
We initialize a variable with the first element and then compare it with the remaining elements using a loop. If a larger element is found, it replaces the current maximum.
 
3. Code
public class MaxArray {
   public static void main(String[] args) {
       int[] arr = {10, 45, 23, 67, 89, 12};

       int max = arr[0];

       for (int i = 1; i < arr.length; i++) {
           if (arr[i] > max) {
               max = arr[i];
           }
       }

       System.out.println("Maximum Element: " + max);
   }
}
 
4. Output
Maximum Element: 89
 
5. Conclusion
This program demonstrates array traversal and comparison logic. It is a fundamental concept used in searching and sorting algorithms.
 
7.1 Inheritance (Employee & Manager)
1. Aim
To demonstrate inheritance using Employee and Manager classes.
 
2. Theory
Inheritance is a key concept of Object-Oriented Programming that allows one class to acquire properties of another. The parent class is called superclass and the child is subclass.
It promotes code reuse and hierarchy.
 
3. Code
class Employee {
   String name;
   double salary;

   void getDetails(String n, double s) {
       name = n;
       salary = s;
   }

   void display() {
       System.out.println("Name: " + name);
       System.out.println("Salary: " + salary);
   }
}

class Manager extends Employee {
   String department;

   void setDept(String d) {
       department = d;
   }

   void showManager() {
       display();
       System.out.println("Department: " + department);
   }
}

public class InheritanceDemo {
   public static void main(String[] args) {
       Manager m = new Manager();
       m.getDetails("Ali", 50000);
       m.setDept("IT");
       m.showManager();
   }
}
 
4. Output
Name: Ali
Salary: 50000.0
Department: IT
 
5. Conclusion
This program demonstrates how inheritance helps in code reuse and hierarchical design. It simplifies programming and improves maintainability.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
7.2 Method Overriding (Vehicle → Car → SportsCar)
1. Aim
To demonstrate method overriding and use of super keyword.
 
2. Theory
Method overriding allows a subclass to provide a specific implementation of a method already defined in the parent class.
 
3. Code
class Vehicle {
   void showSpeed() {
       System.out.println("Vehicle Speed: 60 km/h");
   }
}

class Car extends Vehicle {
   void showSpeed() {
       System.out.println("Car Speed: 120 km/h");
   }
}

class SportsCar extends Car {
   void showSpeed() {
       super.showSpeed();
       System.out.println("SportsCar Speed: 200 km/h");
   }
}

public class OverrideDemo {
   public static void main(String[] args) {
       SportsCar s = new SportsCar();
       s.showSpeed();
   }
}
 
4. Output
Car Speed: 120 km/h
SportsCar Speed: 200 km/h
 
5. Conclusion
This program shows how overriding allows dynamic behavior. The super keyword helps call parent methods.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
8.1 Abstract Class (Shape)
1. Aim
To demonstrate abstract classes and polymorphism.
 
2. Theory
Abstract classes cannot be instantiated and may contain abstract methods. Subclasses must implement them.
 
3. Code
abstract class Shape {
   String color;

   abstract double calculateArea();

   void draw() {
       System.out.println("Drawing shape");
   }
}

class Circle extends Shape {
   double r;

   Circle(double r) {
       this.r = r;
   }

   double calculateArea() {
       return 3.14 * r * r;
   }
}

class Rectangle extends Shape {
   double l, b;

   Rectangle(double l, double b) {
       this.l = l;
       this.b = b;
   }

   double calculateArea() {
       return l * b;
   }
}

public class AbstractDemo {
   public static void main(String[] args) {
       Shape s1 = new Circle(5);
       Shape s2 = new Rectangle(4, 6);

       System.out.println("Circle Area: " + s1.calculateArea());
       System.out.println("Rectangle Area: " + s2.calculateArea());
   }
}
 
4. Output
Circle Area: 78.5
Rectangle Area: 24.0
 
5. Conclusion
This program demonstrates abstraction and polymorphism. It helps in designing flexible and scalable systems.
 
 
 
 
 
